entry.summary:
..NEXT WINTER STORM TO BRING MOUNTAIN SNOW, AREAS OF RAIN, AND WIND FROM LATE THURSDAY THROUGH SATURDAY...
After several days of tranquil weather, notable changes are in store by Thursday night into Saturday as a vigorous disturbance and associated cold front sweeps east across the region. Good chances for rain and snow begin late Thursday across western New Mexico then spread eastward through Friday. Snow levels will start off around 9000 feet then fall to valley floors on Friday night into Saturday morning. Snow may fall in the Albuquerque and Santa Fe metro areas late Friday night and Saturday morning, but little to no accumulation is expected at this time. The heavier snow amounts are expected in the highest elevations of the Jemez Mountains, San Juan/Tusas range, and perhaps the Sangre de Cristo Mountains. Greater than 10 inches are possible, especially above 9,000 feet.
Breezy southwest winds develop on Friday then strengthen through Friday night and Saturday. West and southwest winds may gust up to 60 mph by Saturday along and east of the central mountain chain mainly south of Interstate 40. Winds will then gradually subside Saturday evening.
Monitor NOAA weather radio, weather.gov/abq or your local media for the latest updates on this situation.

entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued January 31 at 9:31AM MST by NWS Phoenix AZ
entry.summary:
The Imperial County APCD has declared a mandatory wood burning curtailment for residents within the Calexico area for Wednesday, January 31, 2024 until midnight.
The declaration of a Mandatory curtailment, when forecast indicate elevated levels of fine particulate air pollution in the region, is issued to protect the public health. Smoke from wood burning can cause health problems. Breathing high levels of pollution from wood smoke can cause breathing problems (including asthma attacks), worsened lung and heart disease symptoms, and may even increase emergency room visits and hospitalizations.
The Mandatory Curtailment rule prohibits the operation of any wood burning appliance during the curtailment period. This prohibition does not apply to cookstoves and those devices exclusively gaseous- fueled.
To view current and forecast air quality within Imperial County visit the Imperial County Air Quality website at http://www.imperialvalleyair.org/ or follow ICAPCD on Twitter, facebook or Instagram (@county_air)
